Evicted Pods

Your application was running perfectly.

Suddenly, a pod disappears and its status changes to:

❌ Evicted

❌ Application Disruption

❌ Unexpected Pod Termination

This is a common issue in Kubernetes clusters experiencing resource pressure.

Recently, I encountered a situation where several application pods were unexpectedly evicted from a worker node, causing service degradation.

🔍 My troubleshooting approach:

✅ Checked pod events

✅ Reviewed node conditions

✅ Verified memory utilization

✅ Checked disk usage

✅ Analyzed kubelet logs

✅ Reviewed ephemeral storage consumption

✅ Investigated node resource pressure

✅ Examined resource requests and limits

🎯 Root Cause:

The worker node was experiencing high disk usage due to excessive container logs and unused images.

Once the node crossed the eviction threshold, Kubernetes started evicting pods to protect node stability.

As a result, application workloads were terminated and rescheduled elsewhere.

After cleaning disk space and optimizing resource usage, pod evictions stopped.

💡 Key Takeaway:

When troubleshooting Evicted Pods, focus on node health rather than the application itself.

Always verify:

• Memory pressure

• Disk pressure

• Ephemeral storage usage

• Node conditions

• Resource requests and limits

• Kubelet events

• Container log growth

Useful commands:

kubectl describe pod <pod-name>

kubectl describe node <node-name>

kubectl top node

kubectl get events --sort-by=.metadata.creationTimestamp

df -h

Remember:

📌 Evicted Pods are usually a symptom of node resource pressure.

📌 Kubernetes evicts pods to keep nodes healthy and operational.

📌 Monitoring storage and memory consumption proactively can prevent production outages.

Every troubleshooting session helps us better understand Kubernetes resource management and cluster stability.
